If you mean it as a fictional proclamation or a piece of dramatic writing, it certainly has the tone of an edict:

“Let it be known: ignorance can no longer be claimed. The terms have been declared. Each shall choose knowingly, and each shall answer for that choice.”

If, however, you’re referring to real people, it’s worth remembering that issuing an “edict” doesn’t by itself create understanding or agreement. People can genuinely misunderstand, disagree, or reach different conclusions even after hearing the same message.

If your aim is accountability rather than coercion, you could frame it as:

“The expectations are clear. No one can say they were uninformed. From this point forward, everyone is responsible for the choices they make.”

That communicates clarity and personal responsibility without implying that others must submit. It leaves room for people to make their own decisions—and to be judged by the consequences of those decisions rather than by compelled agreement.